data.title: Melissa George reprises her role of fraught mother in first look at American trailor of The Slap as Zachary Quinto is in turmoil hitting a child
data.meta_description: Melissa George is back on familiar ground reprising her role as Rosie in the American remake of The Slap, with NBC releasing the first full-length trailor this week.
data.text:
Melissa George is a force to be reckoned with in the first look at the trailer of the American remake of The Slap, released by NBC ahead of its February air date.

The 38-year-old actress reprises her role as the mother of the son who receives the eponymous slap, after a career defining turn in 2011's Australian version, which scored her two outstanding actress awards.

With an all star cast comprising Uma Thurman, Thandie Newton, Peter Sarsgaard and Zachary Quinto, the eight part melodrama promises to be unmissable – as seen in the short but gripping trailer.

Scroll down for video

An adaptation of the 2008 best selling novel by Christos Tsiolkas, the story centres around the fallout after a man slaps another couple's child at a neighbourhood barbecue, sparking middle class recriminations.

The fast paced clip sees an emotionally fraught George screaming, 'you hit my child' as the controversial slap has damaging and far reaching consequences – dividing friends and family.

Sitting on the panel at the Television Critics Association winter press tour at the Langham Hotel in Pasadena, California last week, George revealed she was eagerly following the casting of the American series.

'I was like, who is going to play Rosie, who is going to play Rosie? This is my girl. This is my woman. I want her to come home,' said the U.S based star.

The new mother jumped at the opportunity to take on the role when producer Jon Robin Baitz called her.

'I said, "I am so happy you called because I want to dig deeper", said the new mother.

Speaking of the filming the former Home And Away actress said: 'It's very confronting and I've never felt for a second that I'm repeating something or that the scene is the same... it's completely the opposite.'

Meanwhile Star Trek actor Zachary Quinto, 37, spoke about the difficulty of filming the iconic slap scene.

No child was hurt in the making of this mini-series.

'It was a big scene with a lot of technical elements to it and the thing that was most important to everyone was the safety of the kids,' the 37-year-old said on Friday, according to Entertainment Weekly.

'Obviously we had to do it repetitively. But we isolated the moment of the slap. There was clear communication with the kids. And then all the explosive anger and emotions was done without the kids there. It was really well handled.

'And oddly, for all of us, since we spent so much time shooting that sequence, it was an enjoyable time for bonding and getting to know each other, even though it was in the context of this horrific act.'

The cast had no doubt that Zachary's character, Harry, was in the wrong for hitting the child, Melissa told the assembled critics.

But Uma made the point that 'growing up in the ’70s, we got hit all the time. You saw friends getting hit.

'One of the things I felt about this piece is it’s a very interesting cultural observation about the changing face of how to be a human being and what’s acceptable and what’s not.'

The original Australian version starred Jonathan LaPaglia, Essie Davis, Alex Dimitriades, Sophie Low and Sophie Okenedo.
